<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1930-01-17T19:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1930-01-17T19:00:00-05:00" n="394" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d394">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.05/237: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of
                                    State</gloss> to the Chargé in China</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Perkins</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1930-01-17T19:00:00-05:00">January 17, 1930—7
                                p.m.</date></dateline></opener>
                        <p>19. Your 47, January 15, 3 p.m., 48, January 16, 11 a.m., and 52, January
                            16, 3 p.m.</p>
                        <list>
                            <label>1.</label>
                            <item>The Department has studied these telegrams and is satisfied with
                                the general position taken by the American delegates and the
                                Legation as described therein.</item>
                            <label>2.</label>
                            <item>The Department desires, as soon as the situation is sufficiently
                                clarified, a statement of the points in regard to which the foreign
                                delegates and the Chinese representatives remain in
                                disagreement.</item>
                        </list>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Cotton</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>